actions.comment:
Thanks for the report. The `.lottie` format (dotLottie) is a ZIP container that wraps a Lottie JSON animation — it's a different format from the standard `.json` Lottie files. SkiaSharp's Skottie module (via Skia) only parses raw Lottie JSON, so passing a `.lottie` file returns `null` because the ZIP binary data isn't valid JSON.

Here's a workaround — extract the JSON from the `.lottie` ZIP container first:

```csharp
using var zip = System.IO.Compression.ZipFile.OpenRead(sourceFileAbsolute);
var entry = zip.Entries.FirstOrDefault(e => e.Name.EndsWith(".json"));
if (entry != null)
{
    using var stream = entry.Open();
    using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);
    var json = reader.ReadToEnd();
    var animation = SkiaSharp.Skottie.Animation.Parse(json);
    if (animation != null)
    {
        // Use animation here
    }
}
```

Alternatively, you can download the `.json` format directly from LottieFiles instead of the `.lottie` format — the JSON variant is supported out of the box.

We'll keep this open as an enhancement request to consider adding built-in dotLottie support.
